"><span>Give a gift subscription</span></a></p><p><span>Alexander the Great=
 supposedly kept a copy of </span><em>The Iliad</em><span> on his nightstan=
d and a dagger under his pillow. </span></p><p>His ambition=E2=80=94to beco=
me Achilles=E2=80=94was just out of reach. </p><p>The means to do it=E2=80=
=94a dagger=E2=80=94was directly within grasp.</p><p><em>On Grand Strategy<=
/em><span> by historian John Lewis Gaddis covers roughly 2,500 years of his=
tory, pulling from writers, statesmen, theologians, and political philosoph=
ers. Rather than presenting a single thesis, the book is more of a synthesi=
s=E2=80=94something Gaddis pieced together over decades of teaching. The bo=
ok is dense at times, simply because of the sheer range of ideas it engages=
 with. But it stands as one of the most concise and nuanced explorations of=
 grand strategy. I first encountered these ideas as a student in John=E2=80=
=99s class at Yale.</span></p><p><span>The book draws on sources as varied =
as historian Thucidydes, political philosopher </span><a href=3D"https://ww=
w.robkhenderson.com/p/the-machiavellian-maze" rel=3D"">Machiavelli</a><span=
>, strategist Carl von Clausewitz, psychologist </span><a href=3D"https://w=
ww.robkhenderson.com/p/daniel-kahnemans-final-exploration" rel=3D"">Daniel =
Kahneman</a><span>, novelist </span><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.co=
m/p/social-class-on-tv-shows" rel=3D"">F. Scott Fitzgerald</a><span>, and m=
any, many others.</span></p><p><span>The cover of </span><em>On Grand Strat=
egy </em><span>features an illustration of two ancient Greek warriors=E2=80=
=94Achilles and Ajax=E2=80=94based on the iconic image depicted on ancient =
Greek pottery (most famously on an Attic black-figure amphora by Exekias fr=
om around 540=E2=80=93530 BC).</span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-cont=
ainer"><figure><a class=3D"image-link image2 is-viewable-img" target=3D"_bl=
